    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think this is true (and I think the original statement for <code>ContinuousOn</code> on <code>s</code> not <code>f '' s</code> was correct.) <code>f</code> may map <code>s</code> and <code>t</code> into <code>f '' s</code>, but the mapping may only be continuous on <code>s</code> not <code>t</code>. The inverse is constructed by choice and so it may map backwards into <code>t</code>.</p>",
        "id": 564972271,
        "sender_full_name": "Vlad Tsyrklevich",
        "timestamp": 1766398377
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What I actually want to show in the real proof I'm working on is to infer <code>Set.BijOn (Function.invFun ψ) (ψ '' I) I</code> from <code>Set.BijOn (Function.invFunOn ψ I) (ψ '' I) I</code>. Is that possible?</p>",
        "id": 564975462,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Novak",
        "timestamp": 1766399549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If psi were injective, yes. But otherwise, psi inverse may map out of I.</p>",
        "id": 564977718,
        "sender_full_name": "Vlad Tsyrklevich",
        "timestamp": 1766400444
    },
